WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.044 --> 00:00:08.960
SPEAKER 1: We're back.

00:00:08.960 --> 00:00:10.876
We're going to do part
two of our conversation

00:00:10.876 --> 00:00:11.565
with Sebastian.

00:00:11.565 --> 00:00:14.540
We're going to talk about his
excellent book called "Tribe:

00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:17.730
On Homecoming and Belonging."

00:00:17.730 --> 00:00:21.740
So I wanted to
jump into it first.

00:00:21.740 --> 00:00:25.370
What got you interested
in this topic?

00:00:25.370 --> 00:00:29.640
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: So I had
this interesting experience.

00:00:29.640 --> 00:00:33.170
I spent a year off and on with
an American platoon in combat

00:00:33.170 --> 00:00:37.330
in eastern Afghanistan,
very remote outpost,

00:00:37.330 --> 00:00:40.580
a lot of combat, a lot of
hardship, a lot of danger,

00:00:40.580 --> 00:00:43.414
a lot of deprivation.

00:00:43.414 --> 00:00:45.330
Those guys couldn't wait
to get back to Italy,

00:00:45.330 --> 00:00:46.310
where they were based.

00:00:46.310 --> 00:00:49.520
They had planned a big old
party and imagined things

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:50.330
they had planned.

00:00:50.330 --> 00:00:53.660
And they got back in after
the party sort of subsided,

00:00:53.660 --> 00:00:55.860
I caught up with them in Italy.

00:00:55.860 --> 00:01:00.540
And I was really intrigued
by the fact that most of them

00:01:00.540 --> 00:01:03.180
did not want to come back
to the United States.

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:04.680
They said, if we
could, we'd go back

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:12.600
to Restrepo, this flea-ridden,
scorpion-ridden, hell hole.

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:15.120
No women, there
was no television,

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:17.980
there was no cooked food,
there was no running water,

00:01:17.980 --> 00:01:19.890
there was no way to bathe.

00:01:19.890 --> 00:01:24.830
I mean, circumstances were
brutal and they all missed it.

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:28.130
And it made me
think of something.

00:01:28.130 --> 00:01:30.180
When I was young I had
a sort of uncle figure,

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:32.450
a sort of mentor in my
life named Ellis Settle.

00:01:32.450 --> 00:01:35.330
And he was half Lakota
Sioux, half Apache.

00:01:35.330 --> 00:01:36.910
He grew up during
the Depression,

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:40.220
born during the Depression,
grew up out West,

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:41.990
educated himself
incredibly well.

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:45.200
He read everything that
he could get his hands on.

00:01:45.200 --> 00:01:47.010
Brilliant, beautiful person.

00:01:47.010 --> 00:01:50.420
And I remember him telling
me, this is how he phrased it.

00:01:50.420 --> 00:01:53.040
He said, throughout the
history of the United

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:57.650
States along the frontier, he
said, white people were always

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.949
running off to join the Indians
but the Indians never ran off

00:02:00.949 --> 00:02:01.990
to join the white people.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:06.370
He said, given a
choice, free people

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:09.419
will go towards the tribal,
towards the communal,

00:02:09.419 --> 00:02:10.570
and away from the modern.

00:02:13.710 --> 00:02:15.390
And that really
stuck in my mind,

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:16.860
and I wondered if was true.

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:18.510
And then I heard
the soldiers saying

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:20.220
basically the same
thing, we don't

00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:21.810
want to go back to America.

00:02:21.810 --> 00:02:24.540
And what Ellis told me
was that even people who

00:02:24.540 --> 00:02:29.820
had been kidnapped by the
native tribes along the frontier

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:32.550
and taken back and adopted
into these societies

00:02:32.550 --> 00:02:35.730
into these tribal communities,
when given the chance

00:02:35.730 --> 00:02:37.750
to be repatriated
to their family,

00:02:37.750 --> 00:02:40.920
to their native country,
they would often refuse,

00:02:40.920 --> 00:02:41.960
they'd go into hiding.

00:02:41.960 --> 00:02:46.540
The last thing they wanted to
do was come back to America.

00:02:46.540 --> 00:02:49.930
And I just thought,
what's going on?

00:02:49.930 --> 00:02:52.780
Something is wrong.

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:54.290
And then I started
to look into it.

00:02:54.290 --> 00:02:58.102
And what I found,
to my surprise--

00:02:58.102 --> 00:02:59.560
actually, it wasn't
to my surprise,

00:02:59.560 --> 00:03:02.000
now that I think of it--

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:06.920
that as wealth goes up in
society, as modernity goes up,

00:03:06.920 --> 00:03:09.050
the suicide rate goes up.

00:03:09.050 --> 00:03:13.680
As things get easier, people are
more likely to kill themselves.

00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:18.090
As things get easier, people
are more likely to be depressed.

00:03:18.090 --> 00:03:21.215
As things get easier,
people are more anxious.

00:03:21.215 --> 00:03:25.315
As things get easier, people are
way more likely to have PTSD.

00:03:25.315 --> 00:03:27.990
The PTSD rate in modern
affluent societies

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:31.620
is way, way higher
than in poor societies.

00:03:31.620 --> 00:03:33.504
The Kurdish Peshmerga,
the Afghan fighters,

00:03:33.504 --> 00:03:35.670
the Iraqi fighters, they
don't even know what it is.

00:03:35.670 --> 00:03:37.710
I mean, they really
are quite puzzled

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:41.520
by this phenomenon that
American soldiers talk about.

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:46.530
PTSD rates in Israel
are 1%; in our military,

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:49.420
it's about 15% to 20%.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:51.810
Which is odd because
only 20% of our military

00:03:51.810 --> 00:03:54.520
is engaged in any
combat whatsoever.

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:55.620
Something's going on.

00:03:55.620 --> 00:03:58.920
And I developed this theory
that maybe a certain amount

00:03:58.920 --> 00:04:04.530
of what we call PTSD, maybe a
certain amount of all of this

00:04:04.530 --> 00:04:06.150
is due to the fact
that it's actually

00:04:06.150 --> 00:04:12.780
quite stressful to live an
independent individual life.

00:04:12.780 --> 00:04:15.020
We're a social species,
we're social primates.

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:17.550
We evolved over hundreds
of thousands of years

00:04:17.550 --> 00:04:24.890
to live in tight knit groups
of 40, 50, 100, 150 people.

00:04:24.890 --> 00:04:30.390
And the proximity
of others buffers us

00:04:30.390 --> 00:04:32.580
from psychological stress.

00:04:32.580 --> 00:04:36.480
If you traumatize a rat and
put it in a cage by itself,

00:04:36.480 --> 00:04:39.270
a week later its trauma
symptoms will be unchanged.

00:04:39.270 --> 00:04:43.780
If you traumatize a rat and put
it in a cage with other rats,

00:04:43.780 --> 00:04:46.350
within a week its behavior
is indistinguishable

00:04:46.350 --> 00:04:48.930
from the other rats.

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:53.140
So what seems to be
happening is that soldiers,

00:04:53.140 --> 00:04:56.170
among others, are traumatized
in a group trauma-- usually,

00:04:56.170 --> 00:05:00.010
it happens to groups of
people or often happens

00:05:00.010 --> 00:05:01.920
in groups of people.

00:05:01.920 --> 00:05:04.630
The shooting in Vegas,
that was a group of people

00:05:04.630 --> 00:05:05.530
being traumatized.

00:05:05.530 --> 00:05:06.821
It happened to them in a group.

00:05:06.821 --> 00:05:09.820
The problem for those people
is that that group is not

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:11.500
a community.

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:16.250
That group is not the Lakota,
that group is not Second

00:05:16.250 --> 00:05:18.950
Platoon battle company.

00:05:18.950 --> 00:05:21.760
For that matter, that
group isn't even Google.

00:05:21.760 --> 00:05:25.150
It's just a bunch of people
that got traumatized as a group

00:05:25.150 --> 00:05:28.720
and they will now disperse and
try to recover on their own.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:33.000
And on their own means in their
air conditioned apartment,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.050
in an apartment building,
or a single family

00:05:35.050 --> 00:05:39.089
home on a cul-de-sac in a suburb
where people may or may not

00:05:39.089 --> 00:05:40.630
know their neighbors,
they definitely

00:05:40.630 --> 00:05:45.430
don't depend on their
neighbors, they may not

00:05:45.430 --> 00:05:47.484
like their neighbors, but
mostly their neighbors

00:05:47.484 --> 00:05:49.150
don't matter one way
or another in terms

00:05:49.150 --> 00:05:53.246
of how they're going to survive
another day, another year.

00:05:53.246 --> 00:05:55.870
Now, for most of human history,
when you wake up in the morning

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:57.953
and you look around, the
people you see around you

00:05:57.953 --> 00:06:00.400
are the people that you
depend on for survival.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:03.820
That's no longer true.

00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:06.760
That provides a great
liberation from the group,

00:06:06.760 --> 00:06:15.420
but it also deprives of us
of our most powerful weapon

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:18.630
against psychological troubles.

00:06:18.630 --> 00:06:25.316
And what I found was that when
you collapse modern society--

00:06:25.316 --> 00:06:26.940
I mean, ironically
when you collapse it

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:30.720
with 9/11 or the Blitz
in London or a hurricane

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:32.190
or what have you--

00:06:32.190 --> 00:06:33.750
when you collapse
modern society,

00:06:33.750 --> 00:06:36.600
we very naturally
revert to that sort

00:06:36.600 --> 00:06:41.460
of communal group commitment,
that communal group loyalty.

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:44.790
It happens very,
very naturally, even

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:49.710
in a modern American city like
Houston after the hurricane.

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:50.820
I live in New York City.

00:06:50.820 --> 00:06:52.890
After the attacks of
9/11, the suicide rate

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:56.230
went down in New York--
not up, it went down.

00:06:56.230 --> 00:06:58.120
Trauma is supposed
to lead to suicide.

00:06:58.120 --> 00:06:59.140
What's going on?

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:01.840
It's a totally traumatized city.

00:07:01.840 --> 00:07:04.810
It was traumatized city, but
because we were traumatized,

00:07:04.810 --> 00:07:06.820
everyone knew that
they were needed,

00:07:06.820 --> 00:07:08.730
that their people needed them.

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:10.774
And when you give
people a task, like you

00:07:10.774 --> 00:07:12.940
know what, you can kill
yourself later but right now

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:15.400
we actually need
you, when you do

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:17.350
that, people are so grateful.

00:07:17.350 --> 00:07:19.450
It makes them feel
so good to be needed,

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:23.440
to be necessary that
they actually enjoy

00:07:23.440 --> 00:07:24.910
improved psychological health.

00:07:24.910 --> 00:07:29.100
So during the Blitz in
London, the English government

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:31.986
was convinced that there would
be mass psychiatric casualties

00:07:31.986 --> 00:07:33.360
when the German
Air Force started

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:37.337
bombing London flat every
night, killed 30,000 people.

00:07:37.337 --> 00:07:37.920
What happened?

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:40.200
Admissions to psych wards
went down during the Blitz

00:07:40.200 --> 00:07:42.840
and then back up when
the bombing stopped.

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:46.980
And one amazed
officials said, we

00:07:46.980 --> 00:07:51.350
have the chronic neurotics of
peacetime driving ambulances.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:53.930
You give people a
task, a job, and they

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:56.120
will forget their own troubles.

00:07:56.120 --> 00:08:01.785
And therein lies a great
comfort for them, actually.

00:08:01.785 --> 00:08:04.480
SPEAKER 1: You keep talking
about the effect of 9/11,

00:08:04.480 --> 00:08:06.800
how it had an PTSD
rates for veterans

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:08.752
and also the murder
rate in the area.

00:08:08.752 --> 00:08:09.710
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah.

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:13.440
So in New York after 9/11,
the suicide rate went down,

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:15.200
but a lot of other
things went down.

00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:19.400
The violent crime, the murder
rate went down in New York.

00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:22.640
And Vietnam veterans
who suffered from

00:08:22.640 --> 00:08:24.860
PTSD from Vietnam--

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:27.620
most people don't wind
up with long-term PTSD.

00:08:27.620 --> 00:08:30.530
I mean, from car accidents
or violent attack.

00:08:30.530 --> 00:08:32.600
I mean, it's not just
soldiers that get

00:08:32.600 --> 00:08:35.390
traumatized by violence.

00:08:35.390 --> 00:08:38.929
I mean, there's trauma
everywhere in society.

00:08:38.929 --> 00:08:42.380
Only around 20% of people wind
up with a long-term problem.

00:08:42.380 --> 00:08:45.950
Well, these Vietnam vets were
in that 20% and decades later

00:08:45.950 --> 00:08:48.080
were still suffering from PTSD.

00:08:48.080 --> 00:08:50.300
And they said that as
soon as 9/11 happened,

00:08:50.300 --> 00:08:53.210
they stopped experiencing
their symptoms because boom,

00:08:53.210 --> 00:08:55.940
they're back on the
battlefield, what a relief.

00:08:55.940 --> 00:08:59.100
People need me, I can
ignore my own troubles

00:08:59.100 --> 00:09:01.940
and help the group,
help other people.

00:09:01.940 --> 00:09:04.460
And that feels incredibly good.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:07.850
I mean, one of the sort of
sad ironies of modern society

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:10.670
is that we are so
affluent and so safe

00:09:10.670 --> 00:09:15.440
that individually, none of us
are ever needed by the society.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:20.090
I mean, the society
continues on fine without us.

00:09:20.090 --> 00:09:23.300
Our country and our community
never ask anything from us

00:09:23.300 --> 00:09:24.939
because they never need us.

00:09:24.939 --> 00:09:27.230
We have a fire department,
we have a police department,

00:09:27.230 --> 00:09:28.460
we have farmers
that grow our food,

00:09:28.460 --> 00:09:30.418
we have people who drill
for oil and get killed

00:09:30.418 --> 00:09:32.543
doing that, they've got
loggers cutting trees down,

00:09:32.543 --> 00:09:34.418
we've got commercial
fishermen catching fish.

00:09:34.418 --> 00:09:35.210
Everyone's dying.

00:09:35.210 --> 00:09:36.762
I mean, people die
doing those jobs.

00:09:36.762 --> 00:09:37.720
They're dangerous jobs.

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:40.850
They're more dangerous than most
of the units in the US military

00:09:40.850 --> 00:09:42.740
except the really
forward front line units.

00:09:45.380 --> 00:09:46.980
We don't have to
deal with any of it.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:51.800
And because we've subcontracted
out all these things

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:57.920
that society needs, until
there's a crisis, until there's

00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:00.560
an emergency, none of us
have to step up and actually

00:10:00.560 --> 00:10:04.550
contribute our time, run
risks, contribute our resources

00:10:04.550 --> 00:10:06.290
to helping other people.

00:10:06.290 --> 00:10:09.140
Until there's a hurricane
that hits a city and all

00:10:09.140 --> 00:10:11.360
of a sudden, people are
looking for any kind of boat

00:10:11.360 --> 00:10:14.990
they can get their hands on
to go rescue other people.

00:10:14.990 --> 00:10:18.170
The so-called Cajun
Navy that was motoring

00:10:18.170 --> 00:10:20.330
through the streets of
Houston saving people,

00:10:20.330 --> 00:10:23.330
they weren't making distinctions
of Republicans and Democrats.

00:10:23.330 --> 00:10:25.370
They weren't just
saving Republicans.

00:10:25.370 --> 00:10:27.800
They weren't making
distinctions of white

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:29.450
and black or rich and poor.

00:10:29.450 --> 00:10:30.870
They were just saving people.

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:32.744
And there was an enormous
an incredible unity

00:10:32.744 --> 00:10:34.880
that happened there
that maybe will linger

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:36.026
or maybe won't, I
don't know, but there

00:10:36.026 --> 00:10:38.192
was an incredible unity
there and an egalitarianism.

00:10:38.192 --> 00:10:42.710
I mean, the terrible sort of
class distinctions in England

00:10:42.710 --> 00:10:44.950
collapsed during the Blitz.

00:10:44.950 --> 00:10:46.700
Everyone was sleeping
shoulder to shoulder

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:48.320
in the tube stations.

00:10:48.320 --> 00:10:51.020
There's no rich or poor there.

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:53.960
Bombs don't care if you're
rich or poor, they'll kill you,

00:10:53.960 --> 00:10:55.380
they'll bury you in rubble.

00:10:55.380 --> 00:10:59.120
And so that egalitarianism
is actually intoxicating.

00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:02.840
And as a result, people
really miss those days

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:04.220
when everyone was equal.

00:11:04.220 --> 00:11:08.930
And I studied one earthquake
in Italy, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:11:08.930 --> 00:11:12.490
and one of the survivors said--

00:11:12.490 --> 00:11:15.650
I mean, you understand
it in that area,

00:11:15.650 --> 00:11:19.190
if I'm remembering correctly,
96% of the population

00:11:19.190 --> 00:11:22.380
was killed instantly.

00:11:22.380 --> 00:11:25.350
They were basically hit
by a nuclear weapon.

00:11:25.350 --> 00:11:27.660
The people that survived
were on their own

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.600
for days until the
government got there.

00:11:30.600 --> 00:11:36.510
And this survivor wrote about
it and said that the earthquake

00:11:36.510 --> 00:11:39.640
had produced what the law
promises but cannot, in fact,

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:44.670
deliver, which is the equality
of all men, all people.

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:47.640
Then the government got
there, supplies got there,

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:53.090
and immediately the social
stratification resumed.

00:11:54.907 --> 00:11:57.240
SPEAKER 1: I was going to
have you read that quote next.

00:11:57.240 --> 00:11:59.578
Perfect timing.

00:11:59.578 --> 00:12:03.810
Can you talk about the
beauty and tragedy of safety

00:12:03.810 --> 00:12:06.032
and how we lose the rights
of passage because of it?

00:12:06.032 --> 00:12:06.990
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:10.080
So humans evolved for
hundreds of thousands of years

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:12.780
in a pretty dangerous
environment,

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:16.260
living in a small scale
society and small groups

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:20.340
where people knew each
other pretty well.

00:12:20.340 --> 00:12:24.670
And in that natural
world, I mean,

00:12:24.670 --> 00:12:29.580
understand that humans are
very vulnerable, anatomically

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:30.080
vulnerable.

00:12:30.080 --> 00:12:35.750
We don't have long, sharp claws;
we don't have sharp teeth;

00:12:35.750 --> 00:12:38.840
we can't run very fast; we
can't climb trees worth a damn.

00:12:38.840 --> 00:12:44.180
I mean, we are really
vulnerable in the natural world,

00:12:44.180 --> 00:12:48.300
except that we coordinate and
collaborate very, very well.

00:12:48.300 --> 00:12:49.470
We know how to make weapons.

00:12:49.470 --> 00:12:52.570
We can speak to each
other, we can coordinate,

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:54.990
we can strategize,
we can act in unison,

00:12:54.990 --> 00:13:00.550
and we a loyalty
to each other that

00:13:00.550 --> 00:13:06.430
will get us to even sacrifice
our lives to help other people.

00:13:06.430 --> 00:13:07.780
Other animals don't do this.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:14.230
We're the only species where an
individual will risk their life

00:13:14.230 --> 00:13:17.290
or sacrifice their life
to help a same-sex peer.

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:20.740
I don't mean their spouse,
I don't mean their kids,

00:13:20.740 --> 00:13:24.890
I mean another
male, for example,

00:13:24.890 --> 00:13:29.350
that you're not related to and
you throw yourself on the hand

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:32.030
