00:47:10.822 --> 00:47:11.780
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah.

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:14.530
So we're social primates.

00:47:14.530 --> 00:47:16.760
We clearly were adapted
to recover from trauma

00:47:16.760 --> 00:47:20.650
because the natural world
is incredibly traumatizing--

00:47:20.650 --> 00:47:25.600
forest fires, floods,
predators, enemies.

00:47:25.600 --> 00:47:30.370
If a significant
proportion of human beings

00:47:30.370 --> 00:47:33.610
were psychologically
incapacitated by trauma

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:35.350
and could not
function and it had

00:47:35.350 --> 00:47:37.330
to be taken care of
by everybody else,

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:39.430
the human race wouldn't exist.

00:47:39.430 --> 00:47:42.590
One lion attack in
the camp, everyone

00:47:42.590 --> 00:47:46.330
is incapacitated and curled
up in the fetal position

00:47:46.330 --> 00:47:48.670
and everyone starves.

00:47:48.670 --> 00:47:50.050
It can't work that way.

00:47:50.050 --> 00:47:52.690
We recover from trauma,
we're survivors,

00:47:52.690 --> 00:47:54.340
were an incredibly
resilient species.

00:47:54.340 --> 00:47:58.500
We can survive virtually
anything psychologically.

00:47:58.500 --> 00:48:02.040
It's extraordinary
what we can survive.

00:48:02.040 --> 00:48:05.370
That psychological
survival is greatly

00:48:05.370 --> 00:48:08.310
aided by the
community of others.

00:48:08.310 --> 00:48:10.260
We have a very hard time.

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:12.390
Traumatize a rat and put
it in a cage by itself,

00:48:12.390 --> 00:48:13.870
the rat doesn't do very well.

00:48:13.870 --> 00:48:16.110
That's what we are.

00:48:16.110 --> 00:48:19.030
We're traumatized rats
in cages by ourselves.

00:48:19.030 --> 00:48:21.720
And the problem
with modern society

00:48:21.720 --> 00:48:24.390
is that we go into
combat in groups,

00:48:24.390 --> 00:48:27.060
we come back
individually, and we

00:48:27.060 --> 00:48:29.520
disperse to our
single-family homes

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:35.700
our apartments, our stratified
society where rich and poor are

00:48:35.700 --> 00:48:38.340
not in it together, the
political parties aren't in it

00:48:38.340 --> 00:48:41.100
together, the races
are not in it together,

00:48:41.100 --> 00:48:45.940
and everyone is living basically
in these little cubby holes.

00:48:45.940 --> 00:48:50.720
That does not help our
psychological adaptation

00:48:50.720 --> 00:48:54.050
to trauma, it doesn't
help our healing.

00:48:54.050 --> 00:48:57.530
And so every
generation in America

00:48:57.530 --> 00:49:01.310
has gotten wealthier
and more individualized.

00:49:01.310 --> 00:49:09.040
So my wife is the
youngest of 12 kids.

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:13.610
Her dad was 55
when she was born.

00:49:13.610 --> 00:49:21.309
He fought in World War II from
North Africa to Sicily, Italy;

00:49:21.309 --> 00:49:23.350
south coast of France;
all the way through France

00:49:23.350 --> 00:49:26.320
to Austria-- the whole deal
as a lieutenant and a captain.

00:49:26.320 --> 00:49:28.180
They just kept replacing
men underneath him.

00:49:28.180 --> 00:49:29.920
He was wounded many times--

00:49:29.920 --> 00:49:32.410
I mean, a level of
trauma that very

00:49:32.410 --> 00:49:37.740
few in the current wars I think
have undergone, thank god.

00:49:37.740 --> 00:49:40.950
He came home to
his hometown and he

00:49:40.950 --> 00:49:45.810
lived within a few blocks of his
six brothers, who had all also

00:49:45.810 --> 00:49:47.810
served.

00:49:47.810 --> 00:49:53.980
The transition from the
battlefields to the home

00:49:53.980 --> 00:49:55.510
really wasn't much
of a transition

00:49:55.510 --> 00:49:57.850
because when those guys
got home, everywhere

00:49:57.850 --> 00:49:59.990
they turned there
were other people who

00:49:59.990 --> 00:50:01.440
had been on the battlefield.

00:50:05.200 --> 00:50:09.580
It was a large scale war that
involved the entire country

00:50:09.580 --> 00:50:11.590
in one way or another.

00:50:11.590 --> 00:50:12.642
That's no longer true.

00:50:12.642 --> 00:50:15.100
I'm not saying that as a moral
judgment, it's just reality.

00:50:15.100 --> 00:50:16.016
That's no longer true.

00:50:16.016 --> 00:50:19.240
We don't need a massive military
like we did in World War II.

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:19.960
That's great.

00:50:19.960 --> 00:50:21.535
There's a real upside to that.

00:50:21.535 --> 00:50:24.410
But the downside is that
when people come home,

00:50:24.410 --> 00:50:27.061
chances are they can't
sit on their front porch

00:50:27.061 --> 00:50:29.560
and look around and say, that
guy's a vet, that guy's a vet,

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:30.600
and that guy's a vet.

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:32.183
If I'm feeling a
little weird one day,

00:50:32.183 --> 00:50:34.007
I can just go over
and knock on his door

00:50:34.007 --> 00:50:36.090
and we can have a beer
together and talk about it.

00:50:36.090 --> 00:50:38.220
That's not possible anymore.

00:50:38.220 --> 00:50:40.320
The kind of community
that happens on Facebook

00:50:40.320 --> 00:50:42.900
is better than nothing,
but it's not community.

00:50:42.900 --> 00:50:43.930
It really isn't.

00:50:43.930 --> 00:50:47.040
It's a pale
substitute for sitting

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:49.730
on a porch drinking a beer with
somebody and really talking.

