00:51:01.270 --> 00:51:03.280
Because I know a lot of
ways you can take that,

00:51:03.280 --> 00:51:05.540
but one conversation
that happens a lot out

00:51:05.540 --> 00:51:09.470
here is about the eventual
obsolescence of human labor.

00:51:09.470 --> 00:51:11.830
And I mean, there's a
robot mowing the lawn

00:51:11.830 --> 00:51:14.907
right now so it makes sense.

00:51:14.907 --> 00:51:16.990
So what are your thoughts
on just the general role

00:51:16.990 --> 00:51:20.367
of technology in society and
people being able to feel

00:51:20.367 --> 00:51:20.867
needed?

00:51:24.770 --> 00:51:31.070
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: I mean,
in general, modern society

00:51:31.070 --> 00:51:34.850
requires less and less of
the individual's input,

00:51:34.850 --> 00:51:38.150
and there's a real
psychological harm there.

00:51:38.150 --> 00:51:41.480
So there's one study I saw
comparing depression rates

00:51:41.480 --> 00:51:44.390
in urban and rural
North America compared

00:51:44.390 --> 00:51:45.680
to urban and rural Nigeria.

00:51:45.680 --> 00:51:47.810
Nigeria is one of the
poorest, most messed up,

00:51:47.810 --> 00:51:49.670
chaotic, and violent
countries in the world.

00:51:49.670 --> 00:51:52.850
I've worked there, it's a
very tough place to work.

00:51:52.850 --> 00:51:55.130
The lowest depression rates
were rural Nigeria, which

00:51:55.130 --> 00:51:56.910
is also the poorest population.

00:51:56.910 --> 00:51:59.970
When people don't have
a lot of resources,

00:51:59.970 --> 00:52:06.240
they have to act collectively,
and in that collective action

00:52:06.240 --> 00:52:10.690
they are buffered from their
psychological troubles.

00:52:10.690 --> 00:52:12.274
In the wealthiest
societies, there's

00:52:12.274 --> 00:52:14.190
very little collective
action because everyone

00:52:14.190 --> 00:52:16.940
is wealthy enough to
take care of everything.

00:52:16.940 --> 00:52:21.680
Instead of a neighborhood of
10 homes having one lawnmower

00:52:21.680 --> 00:52:25.130
that they share, everyone
has their own lawnmower.

00:52:25.130 --> 00:52:26.750
That's great, it's
also not great.

00:52:26.750 --> 00:52:29.716
So as you automate
things people,

00:52:29.716 --> 00:52:31.590
need each other less
and less and just engage

00:52:31.590 --> 00:52:32.910
with each other less and less.

00:52:32.910 --> 00:52:34.350
And there's a real harm there.

00:52:34.350 --> 00:52:37.440
And so we know in the
last 10, 15 years suicide

00:52:37.440 --> 00:52:43.380
rates, depression rates, anxiety
rates have all been going up.

00:52:43.380 --> 00:52:44.920
And I can't prove--

00:52:44.920 --> 00:52:47.357
I'm not interested in
proof somehow proving

00:52:47.357 --> 00:52:48.940
that that's the
effect of the internet

00:52:48.940 --> 00:52:51.760
and social media on our sort
of collective mental health,

00:52:51.760 --> 00:52:55.360
but it is interesting
to note that it exactly

00:52:55.360 --> 00:52:59.860
coincides with young
people shifting

00:52:59.860 --> 00:53:05.680
the central energy of
their social interactions

00:53:05.680 --> 00:53:11.390
from one-on-one in the
same room to online.

00:53:11.390 --> 00:53:13.419
The shift has happened
in the last 10 years

00:53:13.419 --> 00:53:14.960
and the anxiety
rates in young people

00:53:14.960 --> 00:53:18.540
have skyrocketed, as have
suicide and everything else.

00:53:18.540 --> 00:53:22.120
So I think the great
lie of our generation

00:53:22.120 --> 00:53:24.250
is the phrase social media.

00:53:24.250 --> 00:53:27.130
It's really not social media,
it's anti-social media.

00:53:27.130 --> 00:53:29.020
It has great applications.

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:31.690
It's great for disseminating
information, organizing people.

00:53:31.690 --> 00:53:33.740
I mean, the internet is amazing.

00:53:33.740 --> 00:53:35.770
God forbid we lose it.

00:53:35.770 --> 00:53:38.020
All of human knowledge
in this little machine--

00:53:38.020 --> 00:53:39.340
I mean, it's incredible.

00:53:39.340 --> 00:53:42.462
But I say it's anti-social media
because when you put people

00:53:42.462 --> 00:53:44.170
in a group-- when you
put them in a room,

00:53:44.170 --> 00:53:46.780
you put them in a restaurant--

00:53:46.780 --> 00:53:48.280
they will ignore
each other in order

00:53:48.280 --> 00:53:52.510
to pay attention to something
that basically is just ones

00:53:52.510 --> 00:53:55.700
and zeros on the screen.

00:53:55.700 --> 00:54:00.860
If you saw 10 friends, people
who actually like each other,

00:54:00.860 --> 00:54:04.054
standing around all
reading their own book,

00:54:04.054 --> 00:54:06.470
you would think these people
need to be institutionalized,

00:54:06.470 --> 00:54:08.870
there's something
seriously wrong with them.

00:54:08.870 --> 00:54:12.150
That is not human behavior,
that is not social behavior.

00:54:12.150 --> 00:54:16.141
And I think it's really costing
young people psychologically.

00:54:16.141 --> 00:54:18.250
SPEAKER 1: I have
an online question.

00:54:18.250 --> 00:54:20.740
You mentioned how important
being part of a tribe is.

00:54:20.740 --> 00:54:22.660
What are some
strategies and methods

00:54:22.660 --> 00:54:25.720
folks can use to find the level
of connection you discuss?

00:54:25.720 --> 00:54:27.400
It seems many groups
and organizations

00:54:27.400 --> 00:54:30.010
fail to give most people the
depth of connection they're

00:54:30.010 --> 00:54:30.882
seeking.

00:54:30.882 --> 00:54:31.840
SEBASTIAN JUNGER: Yeah.

00:54:31.840 --> 00:54:37.390
I mean, a real tribal community
is one that lives around you;

00:54:37.390 --> 00:54:41.282
that you depend on for
your food, for your safety.

00:54:41.282 --> 00:54:42.490
I mean, it's a living group--

00:54:42.490 --> 00:54:44.560
I mean, in the classic
sense of the word tribe.

00:54:44.560 --> 00:54:47.620
We're not going to burn down
the suburbs, ban the car,

00:54:47.620 --> 00:54:50.980
and start living in sort
of collective units.

00:54:50.980 --> 00:54:53.050
I mean, obviously
that's not what we're

00:54:53.050 --> 00:54:56.480
talking about as a solution.

00:54:56.480 --> 00:54:57.670
So how can we have it all?

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:00.910
How can we enjoy the benefits
of this modern society?

00:55:00.910 --> 00:55:02.560
And the benefits are enormous.

00:55:02.560 --> 00:55:07.180
I mean, we'd need a whole other
hour just to enumerate them.

00:55:07.180 --> 00:55:09.100
We're very, very lucky
to live in this society

00:55:09.100 --> 00:55:10.210
in all kinds of ways.

00:55:10.210 --> 00:55:12.910
But how can we have
that and reclaim

00:55:12.910 --> 00:55:15.640
some of the sort of communal
energy and connection

00:55:15.640 --> 00:55:17.450
that clearly makes
people feel good

00:55:17.450 --> 00:55:19.660
and that arises
spontaneously in a crisis

00:55:19.660 --> 00:55:21.340
like a war or a catastrophe?

00:55:21.340 --> 00:55:26.830
How can we have that communal
thing without the crisis,

00:55:26.830 --> 00:55:28.140
without the war?

00:55:28.140 --> 00:55:30.280
You have to do it proactively.

00:55:30.280 --> 00:55:35.270
You have to say, I want
to make that happen.

00:55:35.270 --> 00:55:38.070
It will happen naturally if we
get slammed with a hurricane,

00:55:38.070 --> 00:55:39.870
but let's not wait for that.

00:55:39.870 --> 00:55:41.200
Let's make it happen.

00:55:41.200 --> 00:55:44.477
And I think there's a few
things we could do as a nation.

00:55:44.477 --> 00:55:46.560
The largest community we're
part of is the nation.

00:55:50.180 --> 00:55:54.140
I think national
mandatory national service

00:55:54.140 --> 00:55:55.809
with a military option.

00:55:55.809 --> 00:55:57.350
I think it's immoral
to force someone

00:55:57.350 --> 00:55:58.891
to fight a war they
don't believe in,

00:55:58.891 --> 00:56:01.740
but it's entirely
moral to require

00:56:01.740 --> 00:56:04.620
that someone put
some time and energy

00:56:04.620 --> 00:56:08.850
into this incredible collective
experiment called the United

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:10.120
States and democracy.

00:56:10.120 --> 00:56:12.490
I think it's entirely
moral to require that

00:56:12.490 --> 00:56:14.110
and I think it's quite helpful.

00:56:14.110 --> 00:56:14.957
I think it's good.

00:56:14.957 --> 00:56:17.040
It gives people a sense
of belonging to something,

00:56:17.040 --> 00:56:17.831
a sense of meaning.

00:56:17.831 --> 00:56:22.215
It also mixes rich and poor,
black and white, religious

00:56:22.215 --> 00:56:24.240
and non-religious.

00:56:24.240 --> 00:56:26.457
It mixes everybody up
like the military does.

00:56:26.457 --> 00:56:28.665
That's one of the great
things about the US military,

00:56:28.665 --> 00:56:31.140
it mixes everybody
up and stirs them up

00:56:31.140 --> 00:56:33.720
and judges them
on their behavior

00:56:33.720 --> 00:56:36.180
and not on their skin
color or how much money

00:56:36.180 --> 00:56:37.980
they have or whatever else.

00:56:37.980 --> 00:56:40.140
That would be an amazing
thing for this country.

00:56:40.140 --> 00:56:43.500
And I defy the two political
parties to divide us

00:56:43.500 --> 00:56:47.520
if we have all had two years
of national service behind us

00:56:47.520 --> 00:56:49.620
and we know people from
these other demographics

00:56:49.620 --> 00:56:52.380
that our leaders would
want to demonize.

00:56:52.380 --> 00:56:57.910
I defy the GOP and the DNC
to divide us with that.

00:56:57.910 --> 00:57:02.130
The other thing, I think it
would be extremely important

00:57:02.130 --> 00:57:06.180
as a people to demand that
our politicians refrain

00:57:06.180 --> 00:57:09.630
from contemptuous
rhetoric, I mean

00:57:09.630 --> 00:57:13.500
rhetoric that undermines our
sense of unity as a nation.

00:57:13.500 --> 00:57:15.210
It's protected
under free speech.

00:57:15.210 --> 00:57:17.970
Free speech is sacred, you
don't want to mess with that.

00:57:17.970 --> 00:57:19.830
But that doesn't
mean that that kind

00:57:19.830 --> 00:57:22.680
of really toxic
partisan rhetoric

00:57:22.680 --> 00:57:24.150
shouldn't be condemned.

00:57:24.150 --> 00:57:26.970
And I think if we
asked our government

00:57:26.970 --> 00:57:31.890
to form a committee that would
examine toxic partisan rhetoric

00:57:31.890 --> 00:57:34.710
and condemn it in a bipartisan
way, that would actually

00:57:34.710 --> 00:57:37.440
communicate a lot to
the rest of this nation

00:57:37.440 --> 00:57:39.420
that we actually are a nation.

00:57:42.380 --> 00:57:44.280
People who have harmed
this country really,

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:48.950
really badly like the dozen
or so mostly white men

00:57:48.950 --> 00:57:51.890
who collapsed the
economy in 2008, that you

00:57:51.890 --> 00:57:57.830
can harm this country that badly
and not pay any consequence

00:57:57.830 --> 00:57:59.180
means we're not a nation.

00:57:59.180 --> 00:58:01.130
Bowe Bergdahl
betrayed this country,

00:58:01.130 --> 00:58:04.110
he might spend life in prison.

00:58:04.110 --> 00:58:06.552
I don't think he harmed the
country in a material way,

00:58:06.552 --> 00:58:07.760
but he certainly betrayed us.

00:58:07.760 --> 00:58:10.010
He might spend his
life in prison.

00:58:10.010 --> 00:58:12.650
But the dozen or so men
who collapsed our economy

00:58:12.650 --> 00:58:17.060
and cost us all $14 trillion,
not one of those guys

00:58:17.060 --> 00:58:18.179
was even indicted.

00:58:18.179 --> 00:58:20.720
What's that communicate to us
as to whether you we're unified

00:58:20.720 --> 00:58:22.020
or not, whether
we're a tribe or not?

00:58:22.020 --> 00:58:23.090
Of course we're not.

00:58:23.090 --> 00:58:24.410
You can hurt us that badly.

00:58:24.410 --> 00:58:26.201
I mean, you can punch
my sister in the face

00:58:26.201 --> 00:58:29.100
and I won't do
anything about it?

00:58:29.100 --> 00:58:30.480
That's not a family.

00:58:30.480 --> 00:58:31.080
What is that?

00:58:31.080 --> 00:58:32.730
That's us right now as a nation.

00:58:32.730 --> 00:58:34.550
Those people should
be in court--

00:58:34.550 --> 00:58:35.550
I almost said in prison.

00:58:35.550 --> 00:58:37.560
Those people should be in court.

00:58:37.560 --> 00:58:42.940
And finally, at
the personal level,

00:58:42.940 --> 00:58:47.650
you can go out and find things
that feel communal and good

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:51.850
and feel that when
you're in that place,

00:58:51.850 --> 00:58:54.040
people are judged
on their own merits

00:58:54.040 --> 00:58:57.910
and not for their
role in society,

00:58:57.910 --> 00:58:59.320
their position in society.

00:58:59.320 --> 00:59:01.990
So one thing I've found, I
was a long distance runner

00:59:01.990 --> 00:59:03.460
for a very long time.

00:59:03.460 --> 00:59:06.580
I was a pretty good runner as
a kid, I ran some good times.

00:59:06.580 --> 00:59:10.795
As I got older, I couldn't run
as much and I started boxing--

00:59:10.795 --> 00:59:13.229
a really scary, tough sport.

00:59:13.229 --> 00:59:15.020
I wouldn't say I'm
particularly good at it,

00:59:15.020 --> 00:59:18.730
but I would say that it's
pretty much consumed me.

00:59:18.730 --> 00:59:19.870
I don't know why.

00:59:19.870 --> 00:59:22.450
The thing that I
really like about it,

00:59:22.450 --> 00:59:25.300
other than just the insane
physical effort of it--

00:59:25.300 --> 00:59:28.400
which I for some reason
need something like that--

00:59:28.400 --> 00:59:31.010
what I really like about
it is that at the gym,

00:59:31.010 --> 00:59:34.550
I go to Mendez Boxing in New
York City, it's a basement gym,

00:59:34.550 --> 00:59:39.400
it's been around for 30 years,
you leave your street identity

00:59:39.400 --> 00:59:42.070
when you walk in that
door down the staircase.

00:59:42.070 --> 00:59:44.590
You could be a poor
kid from Brooklyn,

00:59:44.590 --> 00:59:48.460
you could be a suit from Wall
Street coming to work out

00:59:48.460 --> 00:59:50.680
at lunchtime and
there's no prejudice,

00:59:50.680 --> 00:59:52.200
there's no bias in
either direction.

00:59:52.200 --> 00:59:53.590
You're not judged for either.

00:59:53.590 --> 00:59:55.960
You're judged for how you act.

00:59:55.960 --> 00:59:59.500
And if you respect
and honor the sport

00:59:59.500 --> 01:00:02.650
and respect the other people
in the gym and you work hard,

01:00:02.650 --> 01:00:06.590
it doesn't matter if
you are a Golden Glove

01:00:06.590 --> 01:00:10.040
champion or a 55-year-old guy
who just took up the sport.

01:00:10.040 --> 01:00:11.840
It doesn't matter,
you have respect.

01:00:11.840 --> 01:00:15.330
That is a tribal type community
and it's an amazing thing.

01:00:15.330 --> 01:00:17.900
And it's one of the reasons
the poor kids from Brooklyn

01:00:17.900 --> 01:00:20.120
and the suits from
Wall Street all

01:00:20.120 --> 01:00:25.220
go there and spend a huge
amount of their energy devoted

01:00:25.220 --> 01:00:26.720
to this thing that
will probably not

01:00:26.720 --> 01:00:29.510
pay off in any athletic sense.

01:00:29.510 --> 01:00:30.790
But it's clearly important.

01:00:30.790 --> 01:00:32.930
So you can find
things like that that

01:00:32.930 --> 01:00:37.059
operate on those terms that
are incredibly healthy.

01:00:37.059 --> 01:00:38.350
SPEAKER 1: I've got a question.

01:00:38.350 --> 01:00:40.360
On a recent podcast,
you shared your vision

01:00:40.360 --> 01:00:42.640
for how civilians can better
support our troops when

01:00:42.640 --> 01:00:43.420
they come home.

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:44.920
Do you have any
tangible suggestions

01:00:44.920 --> 01:00:46.480
for how Googlers
can make veterans

01:00:46.480 --> 01:00:49.420
feel like they're welcome
and part of our Google tribe?

01:00:49.420 --> 01:00:53.450
SEBASTIAN JUNGER:
So on my website,

01:00:53.450 --> 01:00:56.960
sebastianjunger.com, there's
something called Veteran Town

01:00:56.960 --> 01:00:57.471
Hall.

01:00:57.471 --> 01:00:58.720
And the idea is really simple.

01:00:58.720 --> 01:01:03.290
It's based on ceremonies
that Native American tribes

01:01:03.290 --> 01:01:05.570
in this country would
conduct with warriors

01:01:05.570 --> 01:01:06.830
who had come back from combat.

01:01:06.830 --> 01:01:07.890
It's very, very simple.

01:01:07.890 --> 01:01:11.120
The idea is that
people who fight,

01:01:11.120 --> 01:01:15.400
warriors fight for their tribe,
their community, their people.

01:01:15.400 --> 01:01:18.530
And when they come
back, that community

01:01:18.530 --> 01:01:21.290
must know and
deserves to know what

01:01:21.290 --> 01:01:24.220
that was like for the
warrior and that there's

01:01:24.220 --> 01:01:28.690
an incredibly cathartic value in
the warrior explaining what he

01:01:28.690 --> 01:01:31.630
or she did for the community.

01:01:31.630 --> 01:01:34.630
But there's also a real
value in the community taking

01:01:34.630 --> 01:01:38.430
on the moral burdens and
the triumphs of the warrior

01:01:38.430 --> 01:01:41.000
so they're all in it together.

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:45.790
And so obviously, we live in
a de-ritualized, non-tribal

01:01:45.790 --> 01:01:48.890
society but we might be able
to recapture some of that.

01:01:48.890 --> 01:01:50.890
So the idea that I had
was that on Veterans Day,

01:01:50.890 --> 01:01:53.710
instead of the parade which I
don't think parades have high

01:01:53.710 --> 01:01:57.370
therapeutic value for
people particularly,

01:01:57.370 --> 01:02:00.040
or in addition to the parade,
the town hall gets opened up--

01:02:00.040 --> 01:02:03.110
they're not doing business,
it's Veterans Day--

01:02:03.110 --> 01:02:09.940
and veterans of any war
who served in any capacity

01:02:09.940 --> 01:02:15.530
get 10 minutes to talk
about how it felt to serve.

01:02:15.530 --> 01:02:17.250
And if you say, I
support the troops,

01:02:17.250 --> 01:02:22.650
that means actually going to
the town hall and listening.

01:02:22.650 --> 01:02:25.740
And you might be a super
conservative patriotic kind

01:02:25.740 --> 01:02:31.157
of person who really doesn't
want to hear a Vietnam vet

01:02:31.157 --> 01:02:33.740
scream at you for 10 minutes for
having to fight a war that he

01:02:33.740 --> 01:02:34.520
didn't believe in.

01:02:34.520 --> 01:02:37.010
You may not want to do
that, but you know what?

01:02:37.010 --> 01:02:39.170
He's your countryman and
you paid for that war

01:02:39.170 --> 01:02:42.030
and he had to fight it and
you didn't, he fought for you.

01:02:42.030 --> 01:02:43.220
You need to listen.

01:02:43.220 --> 01:02:45.780
You might be a
super lefty anti-war

01:02:45.780 --> 01:02:50.510
and you really don't want to
hear some young guy saying

01:02:50.510 --> 01:02:53.050
that his experience
in the military

01:02:53.050 --> 01:02:55.550
was the very best thing that
ever could have happened to him

01:02:55.550 --> 01:02:56.900
and he misses it.

01:02:56.900 --> 01:02:59.480
You may not want to
hear that, but you what?

01:02:59.480 --> 01:03:01.430
He's your fellow citizen.

01:03:01.430 --> 01:03:04.250
You pay for that war whether
you agreed to it or not.

01:03:04.250 --> 01:03:07.500
It was your taxes that sent that
guy over there so hear him out.

01:03:07.500 --> 01:03:09.289
You may learn something.

01:03:09.289 --> 01:03:11.330
And everyone might be
quite uncomfortable to have

01:03:11.330 --> 01:03:15.020
someone stand up, and I've
seen this, and basically

01:03:15.020 --> 01:03:18.260
be crying too hard to really
talk coherently because they're

01:03:18.260 --> 01:03:23.360
trying to explain how their
brother got shot and killed

01:03:23.360 --> 01:03:26.570
right next to them and
they should have died,

01:03:26.570 --> 01:03:29.900
not the other guy and they
have the guilt of survival

01:03:29.900 --> 01:03:31.500
with the rest of their life.

01:03:31.500 --> 01:03:33.460
We all need to hear that.

01:03:33.460 --> 01:03:37.320
And so when you do that,
you are basically saying,

01:03:37.320 --> 01:03:40.920
we're a community as a nation,
we're a community as a town.

01:03:40.920 --> 01:03:44.880
The people that have
served this country,

01:03:44.880 --> 01:03:46.890
we honor them even if
we disagree with them,

01:03:46.890 --> 01:03:49.020
but we're here for them
and we'll hear you.

01:03:49.020 --> 01:03:51.120
As long as you need to
talk, we're here to listen.

01:03:51.120 --> 01:03:54.840
And that's an extremely
important process

01:03:54.840 --> 01:03:57.435
for both sides.

